.TH mbswath2las 1 "11 July 2026" "MB-System 5.0" "MB-System 5.0"
.SH NAME
\fBmbswath2las\fP \- exports swath bathymetry soundings to LAS 1.4 point cloud files.

.SH VERSION
Version 5.0

.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBmbswath2las\fP
.br
[
.br
\fB\-\-use-amplitude\fP {\fB\-A\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-begin-time\fP=\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP {\fB\-B\fP\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-end-time\fP=\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP {\fB\-E\fP\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-format\fP=\fIformat\fP {\fB\-F\fP\fIformat\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-help\fP {\fB\-H\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-input\fP=\fIfile\fP {\fB\-I\fP\fIfile\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-projection\fP=\fIprojection\fP {\fB\-J\fP\fIprojection\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-lonflip\fP=\fIlonflip\fP {\fB\-L\fP\fIlonflip\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-output\fP=\fIfile\fP {\fB\-O\fP\fIfile\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-write-prj\fP {\fB\-P\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-bounds\fP=\fIwest/east/south/north\fP {\fB\-R\fP\fIwest/east/south/north\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-speed-minimum\fP=\fIspeed\fP {\fB\-S\fP\fIspeed\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-time-gap\fP=\fItimegap\fP {\fB\-T\fP\fItimegap\fP}
.br
\fB\-\-verbose\fP {\fB\-V\fP}
.br
]

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBmbswath2las\fP reads swath bathymetry data in any format supported by
\fBMBIO\fP and writes the individual soundings as points in LAS format
files, one point per valid (unflagged) beam. This allows swath bathymetry
to be loaded directly into LAS/LIDAR-oriented point cloud viewers, GIS
packages, and processing pipelines (e.g. CloudCompare, QGIS, PDAL) that do
not otherwise read \fBMBIO\fP formats.

For each beam, the sounding position is computed from the ship navigation,
heading, and the beam's acrosstrack/alongtrack offsets, following the same
geometry used by \fBmblist\fP. By default the position is written as
geographic longitude/latitude in decimal degrees (WGS84). If the \fB\-J\fP
option is used to specify a projected coordinate system, the position is
instead written as easting/northing in meters. In both cases the LAS
elevation (Z) value is the negative of the sounding depth, since LAS
elevations are positive up while \fBMBIO\fP bathymetry values are positive
down. Beams flagged bad or otherwise unusable are skipped and do not
appear in the output.

By default \fBmbswath2las\fP reads each input swath file's faster ".fbt"
derivative when one is available, since this program otherwise only needs
bathymetry; ".fbt" files do not carry amplitude, so LAS intensity is left
0 unless \fB\-\-use-amplitude\fP is given, in which case the original
swath file is read instead (more slowly) so that real per-beam amplitude
is available. When populated, the intensity value is the input data's
per-beam sonar amplitude linearly rescaled from the minimum/maximum
amplitude found across the entire input (from the ".inf" files, the same
source used for \fB\-\-projection\fP's automatic bounds, see below) into
the unsigned 16-bit (0-65535) range required by the LAS format; this
preserves relative amplitude regardless of whether the input format
reports amplitude as signed dB (as Kongsberg and other sonars commonly
do) or as raw positive counts, but it is not a radiometrically calibrated
reflectivity value. The LAS point's GPS time field is set to the
sounding's Unix epoch timestamp (see \fBBUGS\fP below).

\fBmbswath2las\fP automatically generates any missing or out-of-date
".inf", ".fbt", and ".fnv" ancillary files for its input (the same files
\fBmbdatalist\fP(1)'s \fB\-N\fP option produces), both to support the
".fbt" read path above and to determine survey bounds for automatic
projection selection (see \fB\-\-projection\fP below).

Some GIS software (notably ArcGIS) looks for the coordinate system of a
point cloud or other geospatial file in an accompanying ".prj" sidecar
file rather than (or in addition to) reading it from the file itself. If
the \fB\-\-write-prj\fP option is given, \fBmbswath2las\fP writes such a
".prj" file next to each LAS output file, containing the same coordinate
system as the LAS file's own WKT VLR (see \fBLAS OUTPUT FORMAT\fP below),
but in the older, Esri-specific WKT1 dialect that ".prj" files
conventionally use rather than the WKT2 used in the VLR.

\fBmbswath2las\fP operates on a single input swath file or on a datalist
referencing many swath files (see \fBmbdatalist\fP(1)). By default, a
separate LAS output file is created for each input swath file, named by
appending ".las" to the input file name. If the \fB\-O\fP option is used
to specify an output file name, all of the soundings from every input file
are instead collected into that single LAS file.

\fBmbswath2las\fP writes standard LAS 1.4 files (public header block, an
"OGC Coordinate System WKT" variable length record describing the
sounding coordinate reference system, and point data record format 1)
using its own internal writer; no third-party LAS/LIDAR library (e.g.
libLAS, LASzip, PDAL) is required to build or run this program, though
the coordinate system description is obtained from the \fBPROJ\fP
library. See \fBLAS OUTPUT FORMAT\fP below for details.

