.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-use-amplitude {\fB\-A\fP}
.br
Populates the LAS intensity field from each sounding's per-beam sonar
amplitude. This forces \fBmbswath2las\fP to read the original swath
file(s) rather than substituting the faster ".fbt" derivative, since
".fbt" files do not carry amplitude. Default: intensity is left 0, and
the ".fbt" file is used in place of the original swath file when one is
available.
.TP
.B \-\-begin-time=\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP {\fB\-B\fP\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP}
.br
This option sets the starting time for data allowed in the input data.
The \fB\-E\fP option sets the ending time for data. If the
starting time is before the ending time, then any data
with a time stamp before the starting time or after the
ending time is ignored. Default: \fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP =
1962/2/21/10/30/0, i.e. of no effect.
.TP
.B \-\-end-time=\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP {\fB\-E\fP\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP}
.br
This option sets the ending time for data allowed in the input data.
The \fB\-\-begin-time\fP option sets the starting time for data. Default:
\fIyr/mo/da/hr/mn/sc\fP = 2062/2/21/10/30/0, i.e. of no effect.
.TP
.B \-\-format=\fIformat\fP {\fB\-F\fP\fIformat\fP}
.br
Sets the data format of the input swath file(s). If \fIformat\fP < 0, then
the file specified with the \fB\-I\fP option is a datalist referencing
multiple swath data files and their formats (see \fBmbdatalist\fP(1)).
Default: the format is guessed from the input file's suffix, as set by
\fBmbdefaults\fP(1).
.TP
.B \-\-help {\fB\-H\fP}
This "help" flag causes the program to print out a description
of its operation and then exit immediately.
.TP
.B \-\-input=\fIfile\fP {\fB\-I\fP\fIfile\fP}
.br
Sets the input file path. If \fIformat\fP > 0, \fIfile\fP is a single swath
data file. If \fIformat\fP < 0, \fIfile\fP is an ASCII datalist naming one
or more swath data files, each followed by its \fBMBIO\fP format identifier,
e.g.:
.nf
 	datafile1 88
 	datafile2 88
.fi
Default: \fIfile\fP = "datalist.mb\-1".
.TP
.B \-\-projection=\fIprojection\fP {\fB\-J\fP\fIprojection\fP}
.br
Specifies a projected coordinate system (PCS) to be used for the output
sounding positions in place of the default geographic (longitude/latitude,
WGS84) coordinates. When a PCS is specified, positions are written to the
LAS file as eastings and northings in meters. The \fIprojection\fP argument
may be a PCS identifier as accepted by \fBmblist\fP(1) and \fBmbgrid\fP(1);
simply \fBU\fP (or \fBUTM\fP) to use Universal Transverse Mercator in
whatever zone contains the center of the input data's geographic bounds;
simply \fBL\fP (or \fBLTM\fP) for a local-origin Transverse Mercator
projection centered on that same bounds center, with unit scale factor and
zero false easting/northing (so that north lies along the LAS Y axis);
\fBLTM\fP\fIlon0\fP/\fIlat0\fP for a local-origin Transverse Mercator
projection centered at an explicit \fIlon0\fP/\fIlat0\fP instead; or any
coordinate system string understood directly by the \fBPROJ\fP library
(e.g. an EPSG code, or a full \fB+proj=\fP... definition). The bare
\fBU\fP/\fBUTM\fP and \fBL\fP/\fBLTM\fP forms determine the input data's
geographic bounds the same way \fBmbgrid\fP(1) and \fBmbmosaic\fP(1) do:
from each input file's ".inf" sidecar (generating it first if missing or
out of date, see above), not by reading any sounding data. Whichever
coordinate system is selected is recorded in the output LAS file's "OGC
Coordinate System WKT" variable length record (see \fBLAS OUTPUT FORMAT\fP
below), so downstream software can recover it automatically.
.TP
.B \-\-lonflip=\fIlonflip\fP {\fB\-L\fP\fIlonflip\fP}
.br
Sets the range of the longitude values used.
If \fIlonflip\fP=\-1 then the longitude values will be in
the range from \-360 to 0 degrees. If \fIlonflip\fP=0
then the longitude values will be in
the range from \-180 to 180 degrees. If \fIlonflip\fP=1
then the longitude values will be in
the range from 0 to 360 degrees.
Default: \fIlonflip\fP is set by \fBmbdefaults\fP(1).
.TP
.B \-\-output=\fIfile\fP {\fB\-O\fP\fIfile\fP}
.br
Sets the output LAS file path. If \fB\-O\fP is given, all soundings from
every input swath file are written to this single LAS file. If \fB\-O\fP
is not given, one LAS output file is created per input swath file, named
by appending ".las" to the input swath file name (e.g. \fIsurvey.mb59\fP
produces \fIsurvey.mb59.las\fP).
.TP
.B \-\-write-prj {\fB\-P\fP}
.br
Writes an Esri-style ".prj" sidecar file next to each LAS output file,
containing the coordinate system used, for GIS software that looks for
one there instead of (or in addition to) reading it from the LAS file
itself. Named by replacing the LAS output file's ".las" suffix with
".prj" (e.g. \fIsurvey.las\fP produces \fIsurvey.prj\fP). Default: no
".prj" file is written.
.TP
.B \-\-bounds=\fIwest/east/south/north\fP {\fB\-R\fP\fIwest/east/south/north\fP}
.br
Sets the longitude and latitude bounds within which swath sonar
data will be read. Only the data which lies within these bounds will
be output to the LAS file(s). Default: \fIwest/east/south/north\fP =
\-360/360/\-90/90, i.e. of no effect.
.TP
.B \-\-speed-minimum=\fIspeed\fP {\fB\-S\fP\fIspeed\fP}
.br
Sets the minimum speed in km/hr (5.5 kts ~ 10 km/hr) allowed in
the input data; pings associated with a smaller ship speed will not be
output to the LAS file(s). Default: \fIspeed\fP = 0, i.e. of no effect.
.TP
.B \-\-time-gap=\fItimegap\fP {\fB\-T\fP\fItimegap\fP}
.br
Sets the maximum time gap in minutes between adjacent pings allowed before
the data is considered to have a gap. Time gaps do not stop
\fBmbswath2las\fP from processing an input file; the option only
affects how gaps are reported when \fB\-\-verbose\fP is used.
Default: \fItimegap\fP = 1.
.TP
.B \-\-verbose {\fB\-V\fP}
This option increases the verbosity of \fBmbswath2las\fP, causing it
to print out the coordinate system actually used -- the projection
identifier when \fB\-J\fP is given (useful with the bare \fBU\fP/\fBUTM\fP
and \fBL\fP/\fBLTM\fP forms, since the specific zone or origin selected is
otherwise not shown), or a note that plain geographic (WGS84) coordinates
are being used otherwise -- the name of each LAS output file as it is
opened, any comments encountered in the input data, and a final count of
the total number of LAS points written. This option can be repeated (e.g.
\fB\-VV\fP) to obtain more detailed \fBMBIO\fP debugging output.

.SH LAS OUTPUT FORMAT
\fBmbswath2las\fP writes standard LAS 1.4 files with the following
properties:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
A 375-byte LAS 1.4 public header block, with the Global Encoding WKT bit
(bit 4) set to indicate that the coordinate reference system is described
by WKT rather than the older GeoTIFF key mechanism used by LAS 1.2/1.3.
LAS 1.4 (rather than the 1.2 header used by earlier versions of this
program) is used specifically so that this WKT-based CRS description can
be written; LAS 1.5 goes further and requires WKT while dropping GeoTIFF
keys entirely, but also drops point data record formats 0\-5, which is
why this program does not target it.
.IP \(bu 2
A single "OGC Coordinate System WKT" variable length record (User ID
"LASF_Projection", Record ID 2112) immediately following the header,
containing a null-terminated WKT2 description of the sounding coordinate
system: plain geographic WGS84 (EPSG:4326) by default, or the actual
projected coordinate system requested with \fB\-J\fP (including a fully
custom definition, e.g. a local-origin Transverse Mercator specified as
\fB\-J\fP\fILTMlon0/lat0\fP, or as a raw PROJ string). This WKT is
obtained directly from \fBPROJ\fP, so it always matches the actual
projection used, whatever it is.
.IP \(bu 2
Point data record format 1 (X, Y, Z, intensity, return/classification
flags, scan angle, user data, point source ID, and GPS time), 28 bytes
per point.
.IP \(bu 2
X/Y scale factor: 1e\-7 degree (geographic mode) or 0.01 m (projected
mode). Z scale factor: 0.001 m. No coordinate offset is applied; these
scale factors comfortably span a full survey within the signed 32\-bit
integer range used for LAS point coordinates.
.IP \(bu 2
All multi\-byte fields are stored little\-endian per the LAS specification.
On a big\-endian host, \fBmbswath2las\fP byte\-swaps every field on write
so the output file is always correct regardless of build platform.
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
Convert a single swath file to a LAS file, using the default output
name (adds a ".las" suffix):
.PP
.nf
    mbswath2las \-I 0002_20180911_020351_EX1811_MB.mb88 \-F 88
.fi
.PP
which produces \fI0002_20180911_020351_EX1811_MB.mb88.las\fP.
.PP
Convert every file referenced by a datalist to its own LAS file, printing
progress and a final point count:
.PP
.nf
    mbswath2las \-\-input=datalist.mb\-1 \-\-verbose
.fi
.PP
Collect an entire datalist's soundings into a single combined LAS file,
projected to UTM instead of geographic coordinates:
.PP
.nf
    mbswath2las \-\-input=datalist.mb\-1 \-\-projection=UTM \\
        \-\-output=survey.las
.fi
.PP
Same as above, but centered on a local Transverse Mercator origin instead
of UTM, and with intensity populated from the original swath files'
amplitude data (reading the ".fbt" files would otherwise be faster but
leaves intensity at 0):
.PP
.nf
    mbswath2las \-\-input=datalist.mb\-1 \-\-projection=LTM \\
        \-\-use-amplitude \-\-output=survey.las
.fi
.PP
Same as the UTM example above, but also write a ".prj" sidecar file
(\fIsurvey.prj\fP) for GIS software that expects one:
.PP
.nf
    mbswath2las \-\-input=datalist.mb\-1 \-\-projection=UTM \\
        \-\-write-prj \-\-output=survey.las
.fi

